<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-03-16T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-03-16T17:00:00-05:00" n="577" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d577">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3299: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-16T17:00:00-05:00">March 16, 1929—5
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>31. Your 41, March 16, 10 a.m. Mr. Cady’s report envisages a port with
                            docks that ships can tie to and discharge cargo and not merely a
                            lighterage port as at other places along the coast. He states such a
                            port can be built at San José for three and a half million dollars and
                            Mr. Cady’s company is willing to contract to construct it for that
                            sum.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
